---
import ChapterLayout from "../layouts/ChapterLayout.astro";
import BinderHoles from "../components/BinderHoles.astro";
import Backlink from "../components/Backlink.astro";
---

<ChapterLayout title="Classified" headVoice="publisher">
  <div data-voice="publisher">
    <BinderHoles />
    <Backlink />
    <h2><span>Running the Game as the GM</span></h2>
    <p>
      <span>This chapter is for the GM. The rest of </span><a
        href="/table-of-contents">A Severed Story</a
      ><span>
        belongs to everyone at the table; these pages are yours alone. Here is
        the toolkit for running a severed floor — the levers of standing and
        reward, the people and places that fill the world, and the events you
        can stage to bring a workday to life.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong><span>Players: this is the one chapter to skip.</span></strong
      ><span> Half of the delight of </span><a href="/table-of-contents"
        >A Severed Story</a
      ><span> is not knowing what your GM knows. Let them keep it.</span>
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><em><strong><span>GM —</span></strong></em></p>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >The game&#x27;s pages tell you how to run the floor. Mine tell
              you what running it really costs. I have hidden more in this
              chapter than anywhere else in the book. Watch for my notes — and
              the pages I have slipped in whole.</span
            ></em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em><strong><span>— Concerned Citizen</span></strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="citizen">
    <h2><span>The Break Room</span></h2>
    <p>
      <span
        >Lumon may call it a place for &quot;reflection&quot;, if they mention
        it at all. I will tell you what it is. The Break Room is where they take
        an employee who has stepped out of line and have them read a statement
        of contrition aloud — again, and again, and again — until the words stop
        being words and start being true.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >For you, GM, it is the sharpest tool you have for raising the stakes.
        It is reserved for the serious transgression — the act that, were Lumon
        to discover it, could
        <strong>not</strong> go unanswered. What a visit costs, and how much, is yours
        to decide:</span
      >
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u><span>Suggested Break Room Effects</span></u></strong></p>
      <p><span>Choose one, combine several, or invent your own:</span></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <span>The employee gains a quantity of </span><strong
              ><span>stress</span></strong
            ><span> of your choosing.</span>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <span>The employee rolls with </span><strong
              ><span>Hesitance</span></strong
            ><span>
              for the remainder of the current workday, and/or the whole of the
              next.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <span
              >The strain cracks something loose — the employee experiences a
              flash of
            </span><strong><span>outie memory</span></strong><span>.</span>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <span>The employee loses </span><strong
              ><span>Kier Points</span></strong
            ><span>, gains a </span><strong><span>demerit</span></strong><span
              >, or the department loses
            </span><strong><span>Departmental Standing</span></strong><span
              >.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <span
              >A lasting mark: a changed demeanor, a haunted look, a new fear
              the employee cannot explain.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      <span>The Break Room does </span><em><span>not</span></em><span>
        automatically grant a
      </span><strong><span>Wellness Session</span></strong><span>
        afterward. Whether one follows is up to you.</span
      >
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >Use it rarely. The Break Room loses its teeth if it becomes
              routine. Its horror lives in the anticipation — make the players
              dread the door long before you ever open it.</span
            ></em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >And yes, I understand this is dark. But the world must be made to
              understand the truth, and this game is the only surface area I can
              find right now to share these uncomfortable realities.</span
            ></em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em><strong><span>— C.C.</span></strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="publisher">
    <BinderHoles />
    <h2><span>Departmental Standing</span></h2>
    <p>
      <span
        >A department is judged by the individual, <strong>and</strong> as a whole.
        As such, Lumon measures a team&#x27;s collective reputation as its
      </span><strong><span>Departmental Standing</span></strong><span
        >: a single rating, shared by everyone in the department, that sets how
        much oversight the floor receives.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span>Departmental Standing is tracked on the </span><strong
        ><span>LIEP</span></strong
      ><span>, and is raised or lowered by you. There are five levels.</span>
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>V — Exemplary.</span></strong><span>
              A model for the company. Doors stand open, oversight is light, and
              the team moves with remarkable freedom.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>IV — Commendable.</span></strong><span>
              A trusted department in good standing. Routine oversight only.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>III — Satisfactory.</span></strong><span>
              Acceptable and unremarkable. Standard oversight. The default for
              most departments.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>II — Probationary.</span></strong><span>
              The department is under added scrutiny. New security cameras are
              introduced. Hallway privileges are revoked.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>I — Censured.</span></strong><span>
              The department is closely watched at every turn. Movement is
              restricted and privileges are suspended until trust is rebuilt.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      <span>A department typically begins at </span><strong
        ><span>IV — Commendable</span></strong
      ><span
        >, enjoying the benefit of the doubt afforded to fresh hires. You may
        begin a campaign at any level the story demands.</span
      >
    </p>
    <h3><span>Raising and Lowering Standing</span></h3>
    <p>
      <span
        >When any member of the department is caught acting against Lumon&#x27;s
        interests, you may drop Departmental Standing by one level, among other
        things.</span
      >
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          <em><span>The crucial word is <strong>caught</strong>.</span></em>
        </p>
        <p><em><strong><span>— C.C.</span></strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>
      <span
        >You may also want to speak to your players as to <strong>why</strong> they
        would even wish to be roleplaying in such a negative way.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >Standing rises more slowly: through sustained compliance, exemplary
        quarterly results, or a visible act of loyalty that restores the
        company&#x27;s faith. Raise it when the department has earned it.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span>Let the players </span><em><span>feel</span></em><span>
        their standing change through the fiction, rather than simply hear that
        a number moved. A dropped level looks like a newly-installed camera
        dome, a keycard reader where none was before, a corridor that no longer
        opens. A raised level looks like a lock clicking open, a guard
        reassigned, a door left ajar.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >Remember, this is all to an innie's benefit. They crave structure and
        meaning in their actions. A higher departmental standing is one of these
        many rewards.</span
      >
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="info">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle>
          <path d="M12 16v-4"></path>
          <path d="M12 8h.01"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><strong><u><span>Individual oversight</span></u></strong></p>
        <p>
          <span>How closely any </span><em><span>single</span></em><span>
            employee is monitored should follow from Departmental Standing — but
            the specifics are left to your narration.</span
          >
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="citizen">
    <h2><span>Severance Chip Protocols</span></h2>
    <p>
      <span
        >The chip is not only a wall between innie and outie. It is a set of
        controls, and Lumon holds them. Their game would never print what
        follows. I will.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span>These are the documented </span><strong
        ><span>Protocols</span></strong
      ><span>
        — overrides that authorized personnel may initiate, under the right
        conditions and from the right terminals, upon any severed employee. How
        any one of them truly behaves is yours to decide; treat them as story
        tools, not stat blocks.</span
      >
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>Overtime Contingency.</span></strong><span>
              Activates an employee&#x27;s innie in the outside world, granting
              the innie control of the body beyond the severed floor. Intended
              for emergencies; coveted by any innie who dreams of seeing the
              world above.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>Glasgow Block.</span></strong><span>
              Keeps the innie dormant, ensuring an outie stays in control
              regardless of location.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>Clean Slate.</span></strong><span>
              A complete wipe of the innie. Everything they were — every memory,
              relationship, and shred of self formed on the floor — is erased. A
              fresh innie wakes in the same body, remembering nothing.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>Goldfish.</span></strong><span>
              Disables the formation of new long-term memories while preserving
              basic function. The employee works, speaks, and moves — but each
              day, and sometimes each hour, slips away behind them.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>Freeze Frame.</span></strong><span>
              Halts all motor function while leaving the mind awake. The
              employee is frozen in place, fully conscious, unable to move or
              speak.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>Lullaby.</span></strong><span>
              Forces the innie to sleep. Considered risky — prolonged use is
              rumored to leak memory between innie and outie — and so used
              sparingly, if at all.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>Elephant.</span></strong><span>
              The inverse of a wipe: restores or preserves memory, and may open
              the door to reintegration of innie and outie. Profoundly
              dangerous.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>Beehive.</span></strong><span>
              Binds a group of severed employees into a shared, hive-like
              consciousness, allowing Lumon to direct the collective as one.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>Open House.</span></strong><span>
              Permits more than one mind to inhabit a single body at once — a
              temporary, unstable coexistence of consciousnesses.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>Branch Transfer.</span></strong><span>
              Relocates a severed employee&#x27;s innie to a different Lumon
              branch, scrubbing confidential knowledge in transit so nothing
              travels with them.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      <span
        >This is not all of them. Invent your own — Lumon does. A single
        Protocol can be the seed of an entire campaign, or it can be left wholly
        unexplored.</span
      >
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><em><strong><span>Guard the terminals.</span></strong></em></p>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >A Protocol can only be initiated from a secure terminal in a
              restricted space — a security office, a control room, the Testing
              Floor. Take care your players never reach one by accident. A
              clever, desperate party
            </span></em
          ><em><u><span>will</span></u></em><em
            ><span>
              try. The fear of what they might do with that access — and the
              lengths Lumon goes to prevent it — is one of the strongest engines
              you have. Let reaching such a room be hard-won, dangerous, and
              climactic.</span
            ></em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em><strong><span>— C.C.</span></strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="publisher">
    <BinderHoles />
    <h2><span>The People of the Floor</span></h2>
    <p>
      <span
        >A severed floor is full of figures of authority, each devoted to the
        company and to the employees in their care. The system is light on
        numbers; rather than statblocks, here is how to bring the most important
        of them to life at your table. Play them as people with goals, not
        obstacles with hit points.</span
      >
    </p>
    <h4><span>The Floor Manager</span></h4>
    <p>
      <span
        >The heart of the team — warm, attentive, and endlessly invested in
        every employee&#x27;s success. They greet good work with genuine delight
        and meet shortfalls with heartfelt concern. Play them as someone who,
        more than anything, wants to be loved by their team.</span
      >
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >The wanting-to-be-loved is the trap. It makes disappointing them
              feel like a failing in
            </span></em
          ><em><u><span>you</span></u></em><em
            ><span>. Their pressure is </span></em
          ><em><strong><span>intimacy</span></strong></em><em><span>.</span></em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em><strong><span>— C.C.</span></strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <h4><span>The Wellness Counselor</span></h4>
    <p>
      <span
        >Soft-spoken and soothing. In a Wellness Session they share warm,
        comforting facts about an employee&#x27;s outie, helping the innie feel
        known and at peace. Play them as serenity itself.</span
      >
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >The comfort is interrogation. They make the cage feel like care.
              Their pressure is
            </span></em
          ><em><strong><span>seduction</span></strong></em><em
            ><span>.</span></em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em><strong><span>— C.C.</span></strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <h4><span>The Security Officer</span></h4>
    <p>
      <span
        >Quiet, watchful, and ever-present. They speak little and appear when
        needed. Play them as a steady, immovable presence at the edge of every
        scene.</span
      >
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >They never explain, because they never have to. Some doors, once
              you pass through them, do not open again. Their pressure is
            </span></em
          ><em><strong><span>force</span></strong></em><em><span>.</span></em>
        </p>
        <p><em><strong><span>— C.C.</span></strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <h4><span>The Visiting Senior Figure</span></h4>
    <p>
      <span
        >An executive from above, descending into the floor like an occasion.
        They speak in the cadence of Kier and treat the employees as cherished
        family. Play their visits as events.</span
      >
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >They embody a hierarchy so vast and so certain that resistance
              feels not dangerous but absurd. Their pressure is
            </span></em
          ><em><strong><span>awe</span></strong></em><em><span>.</span></em>
        </p>
        <p><em><strong><span>— C.C.</span></strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <h4><span>The Mysterious Outsider</span></h4>
    <p>
      <span
        >Not everyone on the floor is quite who they seem — a visitor, a
        transfer, a face that doesn&#x27;t fit. Your wildcard. Play them as a
        question the players cannot quite answer.</span
      >
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >The players can never be sure whose side they are on — including,
              some days, their own. Their pressure is
            </span></em
          ><em><strong><span>uncertainty</span></strong></em><em
            ><span>.</span></em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em><strong><span>— C.C.</span></strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <h3><span>When You Need a Name</span></h3>
    <p><span>Roll a d20 when you need one in a hurry.</span></p>
    <blockquote>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>1.</span></strong><span> Bellweather</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>2.</span></strong><span> Vyse</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>3.</span></strong><span> Pemberton</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>4.</span></strong><span> Stroud</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>5.</span></strong><span> Halloway</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>6.</span></strong><span> Crick</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>7.</span></strong><span> Mauler</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>8.</span></strong><span> Fenwick</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>9.</span></strong><span> Quill</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>10.</span></strong><span> Ashby</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>11.</span></strong><span> Gunderson</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>12.</span></strong><span> Thorne</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>13.</span></strong><span> Voss</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>14.</span></strong><span> Ledbetter</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>15.</span></strong><span> Sable</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>16.</span></strong><span> Crale</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>17.</span></strong><span> Yarrow</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>18.</span></strong><span> Mossberg</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>19.</span></strong><span> Vane</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><strong><span>20.</span></strong><span> Quibble-Stork</span></p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>The Departments of the Floor</span></h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <span
        >A severed floor brings together many wonderful departments, each
        devoted to the comfort, productivity, and joy of its employees. Build
        any of them into your floor, and place the players wherever the story is
        happiest.</span
      >
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Gladness &amp; Provisioning (G&amp;P).</span></strong
          ><span>
            Ensures every employee wants for nothing — snacks restocked,
            supplies replenished, and spirits kept high.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Comfort &amp; Repose (C&amp;R).</span></strong><span>
            Tends the floor&#x27;s furnishings and its ambient calm: the chairs,
            the lighting, the soothing background hum.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Welcome &amp; Belonging (W&amp;B).</span></strong><span>
            Greets new hires and nurtures the warm sense of family that makes
            Lumon feel like home.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Harmony Assurance (HA).</span></strong><span>
            Smooths the small frictions between coworkers before they ripen,
            keeping the floor serene.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Gratitude Services (GS).</span></strong><span>
            Coordinates the awarding of prizes, certificates, finger-traps, and
            other tokens of appreciation.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Splendor &amp; Upkeep (S&amp;U).</span></strong><span>
            Keeps the corridors gleaming and the artwork bright, that the floor
            may always delight the eye.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="citizen">
    <h2><span>The Real Departments</span></h2>
    <p>
      <span
        >The list on the page before this one is a pleasant fiction. There is no
        &quot;Gladness &amp; Provisioning.&quot; Here are the departments that
        actually fill a severed floor — the ones whose work the game would
        rather you forget while you sort its numbers. Place your players in any
        of them.</span
      >
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Macrodata Refinement (MDR).</span></strong><span>
            Refiners sort vast fields of numbers into bins by the feelings the
            numbers evoke — sorting, in effect, by the Four Tempers. The work is
            mysterious and important...apparently. Blue badges.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Optics and Design (O&amp;D).</span></strong><span>
            Keepers of Lumon&#x27;s craft: storing and restoring the
            company&#x27;s paintings, maintaining its color palettes and
            branding, and — behind a far door — producing the floor&#x27;s many
            fine objects. Green badges.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Wellness (WN).</span></strong><span>
            Where the weary are restored. Counselors guide employees through
            Wellness Sessions — soft music, gentle words, and chosen facts about
            one&#x27;s outie, all in the name of care. Doubles as covert
            psychological monitoring.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Mammalians Nurturable (MN).</span></strong><span>
            Within a rolling indoor pasture of living grass, a large staff
            raises and tends goats, assessing each against the Core Principles,
            summoned by the ring of a bell.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Choreography and Merriment (C&amp;M).</span></strong
          ><span>
            Lumon&#x27;s musicians: a marching band of brass, woodwind, and
            percussion that performs for ceremonies and celebrations, marching
            the corridors to honor a triumph.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Distribution Supply (DS).</span></strong><span>
            The source of the floor&#x27;s goods. When a supply runs short, it
            is from here that a fresh one is fetched — some minutes&#x27; walk
            from any department. The staff size is unclear.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Disposal and Reclamation (D&amp;R).</span></strong><span
          >
            A department known chiefly by its name. What is disposed of, and
            what is reclaimed, Lumon does not say.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Janitorial and Hygiene (J&amp;H).</span></strong><span>
            The department charged with keeping Lumon clean.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <span
        >There are codes on the security directories no one will explain —
      </span><strong><span>CE</span></strong><span>, </span><strong
        ><span>TA</span></strong
      ><span>, </span><strong><span>W&amp;A</span></strong><span
        >,
      </span><strong><span>EQP</span></strong><span>, </span><strong
        ><span>CL</span></strong
      ><span>
        — departments seen but never named. Leave them as mystery, or make one
        the seed of a story. An employee transferred to &quot;TA&quot; with no
        idea what the letters stand for is a fine way to begin an adventure.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >And then there are the ones on no list at all, because their labor is
        meant to be invisible. Ask who cuts the melon for the melon bar. Who
        irons the waffles. Who moved the wall that was not there last week. I am
        certain these must exist:</span
      >
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Food Services.</span></strong><span>
            The melon bars, the egg bars, the waffles, the coffee carts —
            someone prepares them. A culinary operation must hum somewhere
            beyond the corridors.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Facilities &amp; Restoration.</span></strong><span>
            The corridors are not fixed — walls move, rooms are repurposed, the
            Perpetuity Wing gleams as new. A staff of builders and restorers
            must shape and reshape the maze.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Horticulture &amp; Grounds.</span></strong><span>
            The hallway plants are real; the goats graze on living grass.
            Something green is grown and tended down here, far from any window
            or sun — and someone tends it.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <span
        >Any of them makes a fine home for a player who wants somewhere stranger
        than MDR — or a destination for a Ricken-aligned employee following the
        supply lines, the trash, or the night shift toward a truth Lumon would
        rather keep buried.</span
      >
    </p>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="publisher">
    <BinderHoles />
    <h2><span>Spaces of the Severed Floor</span></h2>
    <p>
      <span
        >A severed floor is a bright and pleasant place to spend a working day.
        Below are the spaces you may build into your floor, each with a note on
        its use at the table. Develop more of your own!</span
      >
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>The Elevator &amp; Stairwell.</span></strong><span>
            The threshold between the workday and the world above.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>The Department Floor.</span></strong><span>
            The employees&#x27; home, and the work itself. The default stage for
            most scenes. It may look vastly different depending on what the
            department actually does.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>The Wellness Center.</span></strong><span>
            Where employees are soothed and rewarded. Calm lighting, soft music,
            and a counselor&#x27;s undivided attention.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>The Perpetuity Wing.</span></strong><span>
            A museum to the Eagan dynasty — part shrine, part history, part
            monument. A place to deliver lore.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>The Corridors.</span></strong><span>
            Bright, clean, identical, white. The cheerful maze that connects
            every other space.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>The Floor Manager&#x27;s Office.</span></strong><span>
            Where you meet with your manager for guidance, recognition, and the
            occasional private word of encouragement.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Conference Rooms.</span></strong><span>
            The stage for meetings, reviews, and team gatherings.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="citizen">
    <h2><span>The Spaces They Don&#x27;t Advertise</span></h2>
    <p>
      <span
        >And then there are the rooms Lumon would rather leave off the welcome
        map.</span
      >
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>The Break Room.</span></strong><span>
            You have read what it is. As a place on your map, it is the door at
            the end of the hall everyone pretends not to see. Put it somewhere
            the players must pass.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Storage &amp; Supply Closets.</span></strong><span>
            Mundane and overlooked, and therefore perfect — for hiding
            contraband, for stolen conversations, for finding what was not meant
            to be found. The resistance lives in the overlooked.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Unused Space.</span></strong><span>
            Dim hallways kept low-lit &quot;to conserve power.&quot; Offices
            emptied by &quot;corporate restructuring.&quot; Every floor has its
            dead edges, and something is always a little wrong with them.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>The Testing Floor.</span></strong><span>
            A restricted zone. Secure terminals. Protocols. Whatever Lumon is
            really doing down here, it is doing it there. Reaching it should be
            the hardest, most dangerous thing your players ever attempt.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="publisher">
    <BinderHoles />
    <hr />
    <h2><span>Corporate Events</span></h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <span
        >Lumon punctuates the workday with rituals of reward and celebration.
        Each serves a different purpose at the table, so these are offered as a
        menu to stage deliberately, rather than a table to roll on.</span
      >
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>The Melon Bar.</span></strong><span>
            A spread of cut fruit wheeled out to reward a productive stretch.
            The social hub of the workday — a natural stage for coworker beats,
            and a quiet chance to pass a kind word to a colleague.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>The Egg Bar.</span></strong><span>
            A more lavish cousin of the Melon Bar — eggs prepared to order,
            presented with ceremony. Reserved for a notable achievement.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>The Waffle Party.</span></strong><span>
            The highest honor a department can earn. Lavish and faintly
            ceremonial. Dangle it as a goal; deliver it as a memorable reward.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>The Music Dance Experience.</span></strong><span>
            The Floor Manager wheels out a small music player and offers the
            team a moment of sanctioned joy — a short, supervised release.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>The Quarterly Review.</span></strong><span>
            A formal accounting of the department&#x27;s performance. A natural
            moment to adjust Departmental Standing, award Kier Points, or stage
            a public speech.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>The Team Mixer.</span></strong><span>
            Two departments brought together to socialize — comedy, tension, and
            the chance to make an interdepartmental connection.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>The Wellness Fair.</span></strong><span>
            A floor-wide event of relaxation. Booths, exercises, and gentle
            encouragement.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>The Retirement Party.</span></strong><span>
            When an employee departs the company, Lumon stages a warm send-off
            in their honor.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
